Sir George Mackenzie, in his “Science oi Heraldry,” published two years alter, in 1680, gives the same account He says—“Some also derive their names as well as their arms irom some considerable action; and thus a second son ol Stman Robertson, for kiiling of a wolf in Stocket · Forrest by a durk in the king’s presence, got the name of Skein, which signifies a durk in lrish, and three durk-points in pale ior his armes.” (p. 5.)
